ce:section.ce:para:
Numerous research efforts have been employed to enhance the photocatalytic performance of TiO2 via adding a secondary component, including metal, non-metal, or other semiconductor [6]. The photocatalytic performance of TiO2@S,N co-doped graphene quantum dots (GQDs)composites in degrading Rhodamine B (RhB) under visible light was reported [7]. It was revealed that the degradation rate of the composite is three and ten times greater than that of N-doped GQDs/TiO2 and P25 (a mixture of 80% anatase and 20% rutile), respectively. Zhang et al. [8] showed that rutile TiO2 @N-doped carbon quantum dots (NCQDs) has better photocatalytic activity for degradation of RhB under visible light irradiation compared with that of NCQDs, TiO2, and TiO2@CQDs. Lei et al. [9] prepared conjugation-grafted-TiO2 hybrid visible-light photocatalyst for degradation of phenol. Chen et al. [10] fabricated Fe3O4@SiO2@TiO2@graphene oxide (GO) nanocomposites for degradation of RhB under 400 W mercury lamp. Saud at al. [6] prepared TiO2@ CQDs composite nanofibers to degrade methylene blue (MB) and Escherichia coli, a gram negative bacteria under visible light irradiation. They proved that the photocatalytic and antibacterial activities of TiO2@CQDs are higher than that of pristine TiO2 nanofibers. The photocatalytic activity of Ag-doped TiO2 films for degradation of MB under UV light irradiation was investigated [11]. Silver doping enhanced the photocatalytic activity of TiO2 films. Wang et al. [12] fabricated MoS2 nanodots@TiO2 (P25) composite for eliminating of RhB under 500 W mercury lamp. Phosphorus (P)-doped TiO2 (PDT) nanopowders were prepared as photocatalysts for MB degradation by Ganesh [13]. He found the PDT powders display very high MB adsorption from aqueous solutions in the dark. Hao et al. [14] prepared graphitic carbon nitride (g-C3N4
                     ) @TiO2nanocomposites to decompose RhB under visible light irradiation. They proved that the photocatalytic performance of the nanocomposties is higher than that of pure g-C3N4
                      or TiO2 under visible light irradiation. Porous boron nitride/@TiO2 hybrid nanosheets were used for degradation of organic molecules under visible light illumination [15]. WO3
                     @TiO2 composite was prepared to degrade bisphenol A under simulated solar light [16]. The photocatlytic activity of the nanocomposite was lower than that of P25.
